SIMPLE: project
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Project
<hw>Proj"ect</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>project</ets>, F. <ets>projet</ets>, fr. L. <ets>projectus</ets>,
p. p. of <ets>projicere</ets> to project; <ets>pro</ets> forward +
<ets>jacere</ets> to throw. See <er>Jet</er> a shooting forth, and cf.
<er>Projet</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The place from which a thing projects, or starts
forth.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is projected or designed; something
intended or devised; a scheme; a design; a plan.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Vented much policy, and <qex>projects</qex> deep.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Projects</qex> of happiness devised by human reason.</q>
<rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He entered into the <qex>project</qex> with his customary
ardor.</q> <rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An idle scheme; an impracticable design; <as>as, a
man given to <ex>projects</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Design; scheme; plan; purpose.</syn> <usage> --
<er>Project</er>, <er>Design</er>. A <xex>project</xex> is something of
a practical nature thrown out for consideration as to its being done. A
<xex>design</xex> is a project when matured and settled, as a thing to
be accomplished. An ingenious man has many <xex>projects</xex>, but, if
governed by sound sense, will be slow in forming them into
<xex>designs</xex>. See also <er>Scheme</er>.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Project</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Project
<hw>Pro*ject"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Projected</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Projecting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>projecter</ets>,
F. <ets>projeter</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To throw or cast forward; to shoot forth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Before his feet herself she did <qex>project</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Behold! th' ascending villas on my side⟦br⟧
<qex>Project</qex> long shadows o'er the crystal tide.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cast forward or revolve in the mind; to contrive;
to devise; to scheme; <as>as, to <ex>project</ex> a plan</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What sit then <qex>projecting</qex> peace and war?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Persp.)</fld> <def>To draw or exhibit, as the form
of anything; to delineate; <as>as, to <ex>project</ex> a sphere, a map,
an ellipse, and the like</as>; -- sometimes with <xex>on</xex>,
<xex>upon</xex>, <xex>into</xex>, etc.; <as>as, to <ex>project</ex> a
line or point upon a plane</as>. See <er>Projection</er>, 4.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Project</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Project
<hw>Pro*ject"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To shoot forward; to extend beyond something else;
to be prominent; to jut; <as>as, the cornice <ex>projects</ex>; branches
<ex>project</ex> from the tree.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form a project; to scheme.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Projectile</ent>⟦br⟧
